  "prompt": "What causes fluttering eyes?",
  "response": "Fluttering eyes, also known as eye twitching or blepharospasm, can have a variety of causes, ranging from minor irritations to more serious underlying conditions. Here's a breakdown of potential causes, categorized for clarity:\n\n**1. Lifestyle Factors (Most Common):**\n\n*   **Stress:** High stress levels are a frequent culprit.\n*   **Fatigue/Sleep Deprivation:** Lack of sleep can contribute significantly.\n*   **Caffeine:** Excessive caffeine intake can stimulate the nervous system.\n*   **Alcohol:** Similar to caffeine, alcohol can trigger eye twitches.\n*   **Dry Eyes:** Dryness irritates the eyes and can lead to spasms.\n*   **Eye Strain:**  Prolonged computer use, reading, or driving can strain the eyes.\n*   **Nutritional Deficiencies:**  Magnesium, potassium, or calcium deficiencies have been linked to eye twitching, although the evidence is not always conclusive.\n*   **Allergies:** Eye allergies can cause inflammation and twitching.\n*   **Dehydration:** Being dehydrated can affect nerve and muscle function.\n\n**2. Eye-Related Issues:**\n\n*   **Blepharitis:** Inflammation of the eyelids.\n*   **Conjunctivitis (Pinkeye):** Inflammation of the conjunctiva.\n*   **Corneal Abrasion/Irritation:** Scratches or other irritation to the cornea.\n*   **Uveitis:** Inflammation of the middle layer of the eye.\n\n**3. Neurological Conditions (Less Common, More Serious):**\n\n*   **Benign Essential Blepharospasm:** This is a chronic condition causing involuntary, forceful contractions of the eyelid muscles.  It usually affects both eyes and worsens over time.\n*   **Hemifacial Spasm:** This condition causes involuntary twitching on one side of the face, including the eyelid. It's often caused by a blood vessel pressing on a facial nerve.\n*   **Dystonia:** A neurological movement disorder causing involuntary muscle contractions.\n*   **Parkinson's Disease:**  Can cause a variety of motor symptoms, including tremors and muscle rigidity.\n*   **Multiple Sclerosis (MS):** An autoimmune disease affecting the brain and spinal cord, which can sometimes manifest as eye twitching.\n*   **Tourette Syndrome:** A neurological disorder characterized by repetitive, involuntary movements and vocalizations (tics).\n*   **Bell's Palsy:** Weakness or paralysis of the facial muscles, sometimes preceded or accompanied by eye twitching.\n*   **Brain Tumor or Aneurysm:**  Rarely, these can press on nerves and cause facial twitching.\n\n**4. Medications:**\n\n*   Certain medications, including some used to treat psychosis, epilepsy, or Parkinson's disease, can have eye twitching as a side effect.\n\n**When to See a Doctor:**\n\nWhile most cases of eye twitching are benign and resolve on their own, consult a doctor if:\n\n*   The twitching is persistent (lasts for more than a week or two).\n*   The twitching is severe and interferes with your vision or daily activities.\n*   The twitching spreads to other parts of your face.\n*   Your eyelid droops.\n*   You experience other symptoms, such as headache, double vision, weakness, or difficulty speaking.\n*   Your eye is red, swollen, or has discharge.\n\n**Diagnosis and Treatment:**\n\nA doctor will typically perform a physical exam and ask about your medical history, lifestyle, and medications.  Depending on the suspected cause, they may recommend:\n\n*   **Eye exam:** To check for eye-related issues.\n*   **Neurological exam:** To assess nerve function.\n*   **Blood tests:** To rule out nutritional deficiencies or other medical conditions.\n*   **MRI or CT scan:** To look for brain abnormalities (rarely necessary).\n\nTreatment depends on the underlying cause.  For most cases of mild eye twitching, lifestyle changes such as getting enough sleep, reducing stress, and limiting caffeine intake are often sufficient.  Other treatment options may include:\n\n*   **Artificial tears:** To treat dry eyes.\n*   **Botox injections:** To paralyze the muscles responsible for the twitching (used for blepharospasm and hemifacial spasm).\n*   **Medications:** To treat underlying neurological conditions.\n*   **Surgery:**  In rare cases, surgery may be necessary to relieve pressure on a facial nerve.\n\nIn summary, while most eye twitches are harmless and temporary, it's important to be aware of the potential underlying causes and seek medical attention if you have concerns.\n",
